@sotto voce

This is most probably reaching, but as a Manhattan girl who grew up in Lawn Guyland, ELIE seems to be Eastern Long Island Expressway--the road that takes you east to the Hamptons to escape the city. 

And I've read a lot of Wiesel, so that connection seems especially belabored to me, lol. I'm curious to hear what the explanation is!

@IndyM

Thank you, I could rest easy with that explanation!

(It would still be baffling, though, as to why the surname was added, making it very specific, right?)

@sotto voce

I agree with you: it is baffling.

Also, Neal's location says Chicago, so maybe there's some kind of explanation specific to Chicagoland...

@Steve L

Alas, that is the tragedy of it. When I figured it out, I sniffed dejectedly for a moment, looked back at the grid and thought that it would probably be impossible or at least really tough.

Ah well, we know whence the ol’ mighty Mississippi begins its journey.

@HeathieJ

Visiting my sister at her Minnesota lake place last week, one day we drove up to see the headwaters coming out of Lake Itasca, and my wife dipped her toes there. The significant pall of the Canadian fire smoke made for cool temperatures and unappealing swimming. According to the sign, the water carrying her RNA should reach the Gulf of MEXICO around September 3 (90 days to transit). And, for my crossword bank, I learned that the name Itasca was coined by the "explorer" Henry Schoolcraft, guided by an Aishinaabe indigenous man Ozawindib. With the help of an educated missionary, Schoolcraft combined the Latin words for truth and head: 
verITAS + CAput = ITASCA, and apparently claimed to have "discovered" the true head of the river. I guess the indigenous knowledge didn't count. Filling in the answer in the grid, I had to remember my schoolboy pnemonic: m I ss I ss I pp I!

@RozzieGrandma
Yes, it's definitely from the playground not the classroom! 
It's also advised as a way to count the seconds - one Mississippi, two Mississippi, three .... and so on, when playing hide and seek.

@Mady

Yes, SEEPED.

<a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/percolate" target="_blank">https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/percolate</a>

@Mady

I believe that to steep is to soak in, like a tea bag soaking in hot water.

To seep is to soak through, like hot water percolating through coffee grounds in a coffee maker (hopefully NOT one of those old-fashioned monstrosities that were called "percolators!").

@Rich Furman

I came here to make the same complaint.  Also, the Mississippi as a border between Minnesota and Wisconsin is much longer than between Iowa and Wisconsin.

Having lived nearly all my life along the river (in Illinois and Missouri before the last 42 years in Minnesota), I definitely think of the Mississippi as a river bordering Minnesota and Wisconsin.

@Jane Wheelaghan

